<!-- 02: VOWELS -->
<section class="section" id="vowels">
  <div class="section-number">02 — The 12 Soul Letters</div>
  <h2>உயிர் எழுத்து — <em>Vowels</em> as Breath-States</h2>

  <p>Each vowel is a specific shape of open breath. No obstruction. The mouth, jaw, and tongue adopt a position, but air flows freely. Tamil classifies these into <strong>kuril</strong> (short — 1 maattirai duration) and <strong>nedil</strong> (long — 2 maattirai), plus two diphthongs. Duration is meaning. The same mouth-shape, held longer, becomes a different letter.</p>

  <div class="vowel-grid">
    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">அ</div>
      <div class="trans">a (short)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/a/ · 1 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Mouth open, jaw dropped, tongue low. The most natural vowel — the sound of the open throat.</div>
      <div class="natural">Baby's first cry. The gasp. A sigh of relief. Animals in distress.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஆ</div>
      <div class="trans">aa (long)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/aː/ · 2 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Same open position, held. Duration doubles — from flash to sustained note.</div>
      <div class="natural">A sustained call. "Aaa!" of wonder. A howl. A mother calling from far.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">இ</div>
      <div class="trans">i (short)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/i/ · 1 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Tongue high and forward. Lips slightly spread. The tightest, brightest vowel.</div>
      <div class="natural">A squeak. A baby's squeal. A bird's chirp. Quick, high energy.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஈ</div>
      <div class="trans">ii (long)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/iː/ · 2 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Same high-front position, sustained. A focused beam of sound.</div>
      <div class="natural">An insect's buzz-pitch. A sustained whistle. A whine of need.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">உ</div>
      <div class="trans">u (short)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/u/ · 1 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Tongue high and back. Lips rounded. Dark, contained sound.</div>
      <div class="natural">An owl's hoot. A short grunt. A startled "uh!"</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஊ</div>
      <div class="trans">uu (long)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/uː/ · 2 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Sustained lip rounding. The deepest, most resonant vowel.</div>
      <div class="natural">Wind through a tube. A cow's moo. The "oooo" of awe or mourning.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">எ</div>
      <div class="trans">e (short)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/e/ · 1 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Tongue mid-front. Between open /a/ and tight /i/. The questioning vowel.</div>
      <div class="natural">A bleat. "Eh?" — the sound of noticing. A baby's vocal exploration.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஏ</div>
      <div class="trans">ee (long)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/eː/ · 2 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Sustained mid-front. Deliberate, calling, directional.</div>
      <div class="natural">"Hey!" — a calling sound. A goat's sustained cry. Beckoning.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஐ</div>
      <div class="trans">ai (diphthong)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/aɪ/ · 1.5 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Starts open /a/, glides to high /i/. A vowel in motion — sound traveling through the mouth.</div>
      <div class="natural">A cry of surprise. A hawk's call. Rising emotion made audible.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஒ</div>
      <div class="trans">o (short)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/o/ · 1 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Tongue mid-back, lips rounded. Balanced between brightness and depth.</div>
      <div class="natural">"Oh" — recognition. A dove's coo. A moment of understanding.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஓ</div>
      <div class="trans">oo (long)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/oː/ · 2 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Sustained mid-back rounding. Full, resonant, ceremonial.</div>
      <div class="natural">A chant. "Om" without the closing. A sustained horn. Reverence.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vowel-card">
      <div class="tamil">ஔ</div>
      <div class="trans">au (diphthong)</div>
      <div class="ipa">/aʊ/ · 1.5 maattirai</div>
      <div class="desc">Opens at /a/, rounds to /u/. A vowel that folds inward — sound retreating into the body.</div>
      <div class="natural">"Ow!" — pain. A dog's howl. The sound of recoiling. Descent.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="teal-block">
    <h4>The Vowel-Space as an Emotional Map</h4>
    <p>The 12 vowels form a map of the mouth — and a map of primal emotional expression. Open /a/ = vulnerability, exposure, maximum resonance. High-front /i/ = alertness, sharpness, pointing outward. High-back /u/ = depth, containment, turning inward. The diphthongs /ai/ and /au/ are <em>emotional trajectories</em> — sound moving through the mouth-space, enacting the experience of surprise (rising) or recoiling (falling). Duration (short vs long) adds the dimension of intensity: a flash of feeling vs. a sustained state.</p>
  </div>

</section>

