<section class="section" id="consonants">
  <div class="section-number">03 — The 18 Body Letters</div>
  <h2>மெய் எழுத்து — <em>Consonants</em> as Physical Events</h2>

  <p>Each consonant is a specific physical event in the mouth — a moment where the body interrupts, shapes, or channels breath. Tamil classifies them into three force-types (hard, soft, medium) and pairs them by place of articulation. Each hard consonant has a nasal partner — a shadow-self that shares the same mouth-shape but routes the air through the nose instead.</p>

  <table class="cons-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Letter</th>
        <th>Sound</th>
        <th>Type</th>
        <th>Place of Articulation</th>
        <th>Natural Sound Analogue</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <!-- VELAR PAIR -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">க்</td>
        <td><strong>ka</strong> /k/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag hard">HARD</span></td>
        <td>Velar — back of tongue meets soft palate. A gate slamming shut in the throat.</td>
        <td>A crow's caw. A cracking twig. A baby's first back-of-mouth sound. The "click" of contact.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ங்</td>
        <td><strong>nga</strong> /ŋ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag soft">SOFT</span></td>
        <td>Velar nasal — same position as க், but air diverted through nose.</td>
        <td>The "ng" at the end of a gong. A hum resonating in the skull. The vibration you feel in "song."</td>
      </tr>
      <!-- PALATAL PAIR -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ச்</td>
        <td><strong>cha</strong> /t͡ʃ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag hard">HARD</span></td>
        <td>Palatal — tongue meets hard palate. A shushing, sibilant cut.</td>
        <td>A snake's hiss given shape. Shearing. A cat's "tch." Water hitting a hot surface.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ஞ்</td>
        <td><strong>nya</strong> /ɲ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag soft">SOFT</span></td>
        <td>Palatal nasal — same position, air through nose.</td>
        <td>The "ny" in "canyon." A kitten's mewl. A soft nasal whimper.</td>
      </tr>
      <!-- RETROFLEX PAIR -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ட்</td>
        <td><strong>ta</strong> /ʈ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag hard">HARD</span></td>
        <td>Retroflex — tongue curled back, tip strikes the palate. Tamil's most distinctive articulation.</td>
        <td>A stone dropped on wood. A hard tap. A woodpecker's strike. Percussive, definitive.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ண்</td>
        <td><strong>na</strong> /ɳ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag soft">SOFT</span></td>
        <td>Retroflex nasal — tongue curled back, air through nose.</td>
        <td>A deep, rolling nasal — like humming with the tongue curled. Resonance from inside the skull.</td>
      </tr>
      <!-- DENTAL PAIR -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">த்</td>
        <td><strong>tha</strong> /t̪/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag hard">HARD</span></td>
        <td>Dental — tongue touches upper teeth. Lighter, sharper than retroflex.</td>
        <td>Teeth chattering. A light tap. Raindrops on leaves. Quick, surface-level contact.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ந்</td>
        <td><strong>na</strong> /n̪/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag soft">SOFT</span></td>
        <td>Dental nasal — tongue at teeth, air through nose.</td>
        <td>The "n" in "no." A baby's first nasal protest. Soft denial. A door closing gently.</td>
      </tr>
      <!-- BILABIAL PAIR -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ப்</td>
        <td><strong>pa</strong> /p/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag hard">HARD</span></td>
        <td>Bilabial — both lips meet and release. The simplest physical closure.</td>
        <td>A bubble popping. A baby releasing the nipple. "Pa" = father in dozens of languages. The sound of beginnings.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ம்</td>
        <td><strong>ma</strong> /m/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag soft">SOFT</span></td>
        <td>Bilabial nasal — lips together, air through nose. The humming closure.</td>
        <td>The nasal murmur of nursing. "Mmm" — contentment. "Ma" = mother universally. The sound of return.</td>
      </tr>
      <!-- MEDIUM CONSONANTS -->
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ய்</td>
        <td><strong>ya</strong> /j/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Palatal approximant — tongue approaches palate but doesn't touch. A near-miss.</td>
        <td>A baby's "yah!" — excitement without collision. A yawn's opening. Flowing into something.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ர்</td>
        <td><strong>ra</strong> /ɾ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Alveolar tap — tongue flicks the ridge once. Fastest possible contact.</td>
        <td>A bird's wing-flick. Water over a single stone. A purr's individual pulse.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ல்</td>
        <td><strong>la</strong> /l/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Lateral — tongue center touches ridge, air flows around the sides.</td>
        <td>Water flowing around a rock. A lullaby's liquid quality. "La la la" — the sound of play.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">வ்</td>
        <td><strong>va</strong> /ʋ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Labio-dental approximant — lower lip approaches upper teeth. Barely touching.</td>
        <td>Wind through a narrow gap. A whisper's edge. The "w/v" of wanting, of reaching toward.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ழ்</td>
        <td><strong>zha</strong> /ɻ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Retroflex approximant — tongue curled back, not touching. Tamil's most unique sound, found in almost no other language.</td>
        <td>No direct natural analogue — this is a sound Tamil invented beyond nature. A tongue curled in space, producing a sound that is entirely cultural.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ள்</td>
        <td><strong>la</strong> /ɭ/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Retroflex lateral — like /l/ but with tongue curled back. Deeper, richer lateral.</td>
        <td>Water in a deep channel. A deeper version of lullaby — the same flow but from further inside.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ற்</td>
        <td><strong>ra</strong> /r/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Alveolar trill — tongue vibrates rapidly against the ridge. Multiple rapid contacts.</td>
        <td>A cat's purr. A rolling drum. Running water over rough stone. Thunder's rumble. Sustained vibration.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="tamil-cell">ன்</td>
        <td><strong>na</strong> /n/</td>
        <td><span class="type-tag med">MEDIUM</span></td>
        <td>Alveolar nasal — tongue at the ridge, air through nose.</td>
        <td>The "nn" of gentle negation. A hum with direction. The settling sound at the end of a phrase.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="hl rust">
    <strong>The Force Taxonomy:</strong> Tamil's three consonant groups aren't arbitrary. They encode a physics of vocal production. <strong>Vallinam (Hard)</strong> = impact, stop, percussion — the body fully blocking breath. <strong>Mellinam (Soft)</strong> = resonance, nasal continuity — the body redirecting breath through the skull. <strong>Idaiyinam (Medium)</strong> = flow, approximation, partial contact — the body shaping breath without fully stopping it. This is a gradient from <em>maximum force</em> to <em>maximum flow</em>, and every consonant sits somewhere on this spectrum.
  </div>

  <h3>The Pairing Principle: Every Impact Has an Echo</h3>

  <p>Tamil pairs each hard consonant with a nasal partner at the same articulation point: <strong>க்-ங்</strong>, <strong>ச்-ஞ்</strong>, <strong>ட்-ண்</strong>, <strong>த்-ந்</strong>, <strong>ப்-ம்</strong>. Same mouth position, different air routing. The hard version is a strike; the soft version is the resonance that follows. This is acoustic physics encoded in alphabet structure — every percussion has a sustain, every impact has a hum.</p>

</section>

