<!-- 06: JOURNEY -->
<section class="section" id="journey">
  <div class="section-number">06 — The Complete Pathway</div>
  <h2>From <em>Cry</em> to Expression to <em>Logic</em></h2>

  <p>Here is the complete journey — how raw sound becomes structured expression, traced through Tamil's own architecture:</p>

  <div class="journey">
    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 0: Silence (ஃ)</h4>
      <p>Before sound, there is the null state. The held breath. The Aayutham. Potential energy before release.</p>
      <div class="example">ஃ → The pause before the cry. The space between heartbeats.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 1: Pure Breath — Vowels (உயிர்)</h4>
      <p>The first release. Open airflow. No learned coordination. A baby cries: /a/. A bird sings: /i/. Wind moves: /u/. These are not words — they are <strong>states of being expressed as sound</strong>. Each vowel is a different aperture of the body, a different emotional position.</p>
      <div class="example">அ → the open gasp (surprise, birth, openness)<br>இ → the sharp squeal (alert, pointing, bright)<br>உ → the deep hum (inward, contained, dark)</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 2: Physical Shaping — Consonants (மெய்)</h4>
      <p>The body learns to shape breath. Lips close: /p/. Tongue strikes: /t/. Throat catches: /k/. These are <strong>events</strong> — moments of contact. Animals make them too: the percussive "k" in a crow's call, the nasal "m" of a cow. But consonants alone are half-sounds — they cannot sustain. They need vowels to live.</p>
      <div class="example">க் → the crack (impact, beginning, gate-opening)<br>ம் → the hum (closure, comfort, mother)<br>ற் → the roll (sustained vibration, thunder, purring)</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 3: Living Syllables — Uyirmei (உயிர்மெய்)</h4>
      <p>Soul enters body. Consonant + vowel = pronounceable syllable. "Ka," "ma," "pa," "ta." This is where <strong>babbling</strong> lives — "ma-ma-ma," "ba-ba-ba." The baby has discovered composition: two elements combine to produce something neither could be alone. This is the birth of <em>meaning-potential</em>.</p>
      <div class="example">ம + அ = ம (ma) → first syllable of "amma" (mother)<br>ப + அ = ப (pa) → first syllable of "appa" (father)<br>Baby's discovery: combination creates new things.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 4: Sound-Mimicry — Onomatopoeia (ஒலிக்குறிப்பு)</h4>
      <p>The first bridge from sound to meaning. Tamil's <strong>irattai kilavi</strong> (doubled words) are sounds that mimic reality: <em>sala sala</em> (flowing water), <em>gada gada</em> (rushing/rattling), <em>kala kala</em> (hearty laughter), <em>gudu gudu</em> (bubbling). These are not arbitrary symbols — they are <strong>vocal imitations of the world</strong>. The sound IS the meaning. Reduplication (doubling) intensifies and sustains the imitation, just as a baby repeats syllables to practice control.</p>
      <div class="example">சல சல (sala sala) → water flowing over stones<br>கல கல (kala kala) → cascading laughter<br>குடு குடு (gudu gudu) → bubbling, gurgling<br>பர பர (para para) → rustling, scattered movement</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 5: Root Words — Named Things</h4>
      <p>Syllables attach to objects and actions. <em>Amma</em> (mother) — the /m/ of nursing given a name. <em>Neer</em> (water) — the nasal-liquid flow of the sounds mirrors the substance. <em>Kaal</em> (leg/wind) — the velar stop + long open vowel = something that strikes and moves. Not all roots are onomatopoeic, but many carry <strong>phonesthetic echoes</strong> — the texture of the sound hints at the texture of the thing.</p>
      <div class="example">அம்மா (amma) → mother (from nursing murmur /m/)<br>நீர் (neer) → water (nasal + flowing vowel)<br>காற்று (kaatru) → wind (velar + open + trill = rushing air)</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 6: Agglutination — Composed Meaning</h4>
      <p>Root words receive suffixes that add grammatical meaning: case, number, tense, person. Each suffix is a morpheme — a minimal unit of meaning. They chain together with no theoretical limit. <strong>This is where sound becomes logic.</strong> The physical act of stacking sounds becomes the intellectual act of stacking concepts.</p>
      <div class="example">போ (po) → go<br>போக (poka) → to go (infinitive)<br>போகமுடியாத (pokamuṭiyāta) → unable to go<br>போகமுடியாதவர்கள் (pokamuṭiyātavarkaḷ) → those who cannot go<br>போகமுடியாதவர்களுக்காக (pokamuṭiyātavarkaḷukkāka) → for the sake of those who cannot go</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot"></div><div class="journey-stem"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 7: Sentence — Context Before Resolution</h4>
      <p>SOV structure. Subject and object are established first — the scene is set, the actors positioned — and only then does the verb resolve the action. This is <strong>delayed resolution</strong>: the listener holds uncertainty until the final element. The sentence itself is a journey from context to conclusion.</p>
      <div class="example">நான் புத்தகம் வாங்கினேன்<br>(nān pustakam vaṅkinēṉ)<br>I + book + bought = "I bought a book"<br>The verb is the final key that unlocks everything before it.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="journey-line"><div class="journey-dot" style="background:var(--teal)"></div><div class="journey-stem" style="background:var(--teal)"></div></div>
    <div class="journey-content">
      <h4>Layer 8: Poetry — Sound Returns to Feeling</h4>
      <p>At the highest level, the structured language circles back to its origins. Sangam poets use natural imagery (landscape, flora, fauna) to convey emotion <em>without naming it</em>. The reader must reverse the journey — from structured words back to felt experience. The sounds themselves carry the feeling: liquid /l/ for flowing, percussive /ṭ/ for impact, nasal /m/ for intimacy. Poetry is the moment where logical structure dissolves back into the primal sound-feeling it emerged from.</p>
      <div class="example">The circle completes:<br>Silence → Breath → Body → Syllable → Mimicry → Name → Logic → Feeling → Silence</div>
    </div>
  </div>

</section>

