<!-- 07: STRUCTURE -->
<section class="section" id="structure">
  <div class="section-number">07 — The Logic Embedded in Sound</div>
  <h2>How Tamil Makes <em>Sound Logical</em></h2>

  <h3>Principle 1: Phonetic Consistency</h3>
  <p>Every Tamil character maps to exactly one sound. No exceptions, no silent letters, no ambiguity. If you can see the character, you know how to pronounce it. The script is a <strong>perfect function</strong>: one input, one output. This is the first logical property — determinism.</p>

  <h3>Principle 2: Combinatorial Completeness</h3>
  <p>The uyirmei matrix is a Cartesian product: 18 consonants × 12 vowels = 216 combinations. Every possible pairing exists. There are no gaps, no arbitrary exclusions. This is the second logical property — completeness. The system generates all possibilities from its axioms.</p>

  <h3>Principle 3: Classification by Production, Not Convention</h3>
  <p>Tamil classifies sounds by <em>how the body makes them</em> — place of articulation (where in the mouth), manner (stop, nasal, approximant), and force (hard, soft, medium). This is not arbitrary naming — it is <strong>empirical taxonomy</strong>. The categories reflect physical reality, not cultural convention. The same system a modern phonetician would use, formalized two millennia earlier.</p>

  <h3>Principle 4: Paired Opposites</h3>
  <p>Every hard consonant has a nasal partner. Every short vowel has a long counterpart. The system is built on <strong>complementary pairs</strong> — not random sets. This encodes a dialectical logic: for every strike, there is a resonance. For every flash, there is a sustained state. Opposition is built into the atoms of the language.</p>

  <h3>Principle 5: Duration as Dimension</h3>
  <p>The maattirai system gives time a structural role in meaning. A short vowel (1 unit) and a long vowel (2 units) are <em>different letters</em> — different identities — despite having the same mouth position. This treats <strong>time as a first-class axis of meaning</strong>, not an afterthought. The same form, extended, becomes a different thing. A principle that resonates with your framework: oscillation and duration change the identity of a state.</p>

  <div class="teal-block">
    <h4>The Design Principle for Your New Language</h4>
    <p>Tamil proves that a phonetic system can be simultaneously: <strong>natural</strong> (rooted in the sounds all creatures make), <strong>systematic</strong> (combinatorially complete, deterministic, classified by physical production), and <strong>philosophical</strong> (encoding soul/body dualism, the null state, paired opposites, and time-as-meaning directly into the script). Your new language should preserve all three — and add the dimensions Tamil is missing: a gradient of awareness (not binary), a grammar for silence, and sound-shapes for states of becoming that no natural language has yet named.</p>
